{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17635609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17635609"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:21:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:21:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17546"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17546"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78227"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10236"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63636"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23938"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23941"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26820"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78227"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of severe pain in his right shoulder and arm. The pain was initially intense and has now resolved, but he has noticed weakness and wasting of the muscles in his right arm. He has type 2 diabetes for which he takes metformin. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is noticeable atrophy of the deltoid and biceps muscles on the right side, with reduced strength in shoulder abduction and elbow flexion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pathologies is most likely being described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Brachial plexopathy","Peroneal neuropathy","Hereditary neuropathy","Diabetic neuropathy","Ulnar neuropathy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrachial plexopathy\u003C/strong\u003E, which often begins with severe unilateral pain in the shoulder or arm, followed by weakness and muscle wasting. This pattern is typical of neuralgic amyotrophy, also known as Parsonage-Turner syndrome, which affects the brachial plexus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeroneal neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with foot drop and sensory changes over the dorsum of the foot, not with shoulder pain and arm weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHereditary neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E often presents with a more gradual onset of symptoms and is usually bilateral, affecting both sensory and motor nerves over time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E is usually a distal symmetric polyneuropathy, presenting with sensory loss and pain in the feet and hands, rather than acute shoulder pain and arm weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlnar neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E would present with sensory changes and weakness in the ulnar distribution of the hand, not with shoulder pain and arm muscle wasting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Brachial plexopathy can present with severe unilateral pain followed by weakness and muscle wasting.","The progression from pain to weakness and wasting is characteristic of certain neuropathies.","Differentiating between types of neuropathies requires careful consideration of symptom progression and distribution."],"references":["Khadilkar SV, Khade SS. Brachial plexopathy. Ann Indian Acad Neurol. 2013 Jan;16(1):12-8. doi: 10.4103/0972-2327.107675. PMID: 23661957; PMCID: PMC3644772.","Rubin DI. Brachial and lumbosacral plexopathies: A review. Clin Neurophysiol Pract. 2020 Aug 13;5:173-193. doi: 10.1016/j.cnp.2020.07.005. PMID: 32954064; PMCID: PMC7484503.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Science","Merryman J, Varacallo M. Klumpke Palsy. 2023 Aug 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30285395"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63636"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17546"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63636"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T21:50:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T21:50:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10236"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78227"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4947"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude7a","name":"Introduction to Clinical Sciences ","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"contributions","id":"23938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/contributions/23938"},"attributes":{"finalizedAt":"2024-12-18T00:56:59+10:30","userDetails":{"name":"Karan Varshney","title":"","isExpert":false,"position":"","training":"Student","credentials":"","institutionOther":"Deakin University"}},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10236"}},"contributionTier":{"data":{"type":"contributionTiers","id":"1"}},"user":{"data"